title="Forester 4.2 › new query language"><fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00WK.xml"
addr="jms-00WK"
title="Forester 4.2">Forester 4.2</fr:link> › new query language</fr:link> › new syntax for set operations</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WS</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Intersections of queries are formed using a <fr:em>variadic</fr:em> constructor <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/isect]]></fr:code>. For example, the following computes the intersection of the queries <fr:code>q1</fr:code>, <fr:code>q2</fr:code>, and <fr:code>q3</fr:code>:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\query/isect{q1}{q2}{q3}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>Unions of queries are formed similarly using the variadic <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/union]]></fr:code> constructor. The complement of a query <fr:code>q</fr:code> is written <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/compl{q}]]></fr:code>.</fr:p><fr:p><fr:strong>Note:</fr:strong> as before, to render the results of a query you must use the <fr:code><![CDATA[\query]]></fr:code> command; for example:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\query{
 \query/isect{q1}{q2}{q3}
}]]></fr:pre></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
