xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:title>Context</fr:title><fr:authors /></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="true"
expanded="false"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>981</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00WS</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00WS.xml</fr:route><fr:title><fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00WK.xml"
addr="jms-00WK"
title="Forester 4.2">Forester 4.2</fr:link> › new query language</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WK</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The existing querying feature, <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-0066.xml"
addr="jms-0066"
title="Forester 2.2 › queries">introduced in Forester 2.2</fr:link>, has been replaced by something much better — at the cost of a breaking change that will require existing queries to be rewritten.</fr:p><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>646</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00WU</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00WU.xml</fr:route><fr:title>New syntax for set operations</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WS</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Intersections of queries are formed using a <fr:em>variadic</fr:em> constructor <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/isect]]></fr:code>. For example, the following computes the intersection of the queries <fr:code>q1</fr:code>, <fr:code>q2</fr:code>, and <fr:code>q3</fr:code>:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\query/isect{q1}{q2}{q3}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>Unions of queries are formed similarly using the variadic <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/union]]></fr:code> constructor. The complement of a query <fr:code>q</fr:code> is written <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/compl{q}]]></fr:code>.</fr:p><fr:p><fr:strong>Note:</fr:strong> as before, to render the results of a query you must use the <fr:code><![CDATA[\query]]></fr:code> command; for example:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\query{
 \query/isect{q1}{q2}{q3}
}]]></fr:pre></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>648</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00WV</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00WV.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Query operations are first-class values</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WS</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Previously, the built-in query operations were written like <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/and]]></fr:code>, etc.; these names, however, were hard-coded into the lexer which meant that they did not work in the expected way with <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-005P.xml"
addr="jms-005P"
title="Forester">Forester</fr:link>’s hierarchical namespacing. This hardcoding has been removed, and query operations are treated as first-class values that are resolved from primitive names in the <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/]]></fr:code> namespace. As such, the following code is equivalent to <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/compl{\query/taxon{theorem}}]]></fr:code>:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\scope{
 \open\query
 \compl{\taxon{theorem}}
}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>A further consequence of this change is that queries can be defined compositionally by macros.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>650</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00WW</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00WW.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Relational queries</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WS</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The most significant user-facing change to the query language is the ability to form basic <fr:em>relational</fr:em> queries along several <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00WX.xml"
addr="jms-00WX"
title="Forester 4.2 › new query language › relational queries › built-in relation symbols">built-in relation-symbols</fr:link>; in fact, the built-in query constructors <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/taxon]]></fr:code>, <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/tag]]></fr:code>, and <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/author]]></fr:code> are all expressible in these terms.</fr:p><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>652</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00WX</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00WX.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Built-in relation symbols</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WW</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-005P.xml"
addr="jms-005P"
title="Forester">Forester</fr:link> includes several built-in relation symbols, maintained as graphs that are accumulated during evaluation:</fr:p><fr:ul><fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\rel/transclusion]]></fr:code> contains an edge from <fr:code>x</fr:code> to <fr:code>y</fr:code> when <fr:code>x</fr:code> directly transcludes <fr:code>y</fr:code>, i.e. contains <fr:code><![CDATA[\transclude{y}]]></fr:code>.</fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\rel/links]]></fr:code> contains an edge from <fr:code>x</fr:code> to <fr:code>y</fr:code> when <fr:code>x</fr:code> links to <fr:code>y</fr:code>, i.e. contains something like <fr:code><![CDATA[[...](y)]]></fr:code> or <fr:code><![CDATA[[[y]]]]></fr:code>.</fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\rel/taxa]]></fr:code> contains an edge from <fr:code>x</fr:code> to <fr:code>y</fr:code> when <fr:code>x</fr:code> has taxon <fr:code>y</fr:code>, i.e. contains <fr:code><![CDATA[\taxon{y}]]></fr:code>.</fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\rel/tags]]></fr:code> contains an edge from <fr:code>x</fr:code> to <fr:code>y</fr:code> when <fr:code>x</fr:code> has tag <fr:code>y</fr:code>, i.e. contains <fr:code><![CDATA[\tag{y}]]></fr:code>.</fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\rel/authors]]></fr:code> contains an edge from <fr:code>x</fr:code> to <fr:code>y</fr:code> when <fr:code>x</fr:code> has author <fr:code>y</fr:code>, i.e. contains <fr:code><![CDATA[\author{y}]]></fr:code>.</fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\rel/contributors]]></fr:code> contains an edge from <fr:code>x</fr:code> to <fr:code>y</fr:code> when <fr:code>x</fr:code> is a tree with contributor <fr:code>y</fr:code>, i.e. contains <fr:code><![CDATA[\contributor{y}]]></fr:code>.</fr:li></fr:ul><fr:p>The implementation supports arbitrarily many relation symbols, even dynamically generated ones; this is not yet exposed to the user, but could in the future be employed by advanced users of <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-005P.xml"
addr="jms-005P"
title="Forester">Forester</fr:link> to support the development of sophisticated ontologies.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>654</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00WZ</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00WZ.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Query modes and polarities</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WW</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Given an address <fr:code>x</fr:code> and a relation symbol <fr:code>r</fr:code>, there are several useful queries that we might wish to make:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>We might wish to find all <fr:em>incoming</fr:em> edges to <fr:code>x</fr:code> in <fr:code>r</fr:code>, or we may wish to find all <fr:em>outgoing</fr:em> edges from <fr:code>x</fr:code> in <fr:code>r</fr:code>. We shall refer to the differenec between incoming and outgoing edges is referred to as a <fr:em>polarity</fr:em>.</fr:li>
    <fr:li>Rather than searching for edges, we may wish to search for <fr:em>paths</fr:em> — which corresponds to passing from a relation to its preorder reflection. We will refer to this distinction as a <fr:em>mode</fr:em>.</fr:li></fr:ol><fr:p><fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-005P.xml"
addr="jms-005P"
title="Forester">Forester</fr:link> supports both polarities and modes for relational queries via the following built-in constants:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\query/incoming]]></fr:code> and <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/outgoing]]></fr:code> denote the two polarities.</fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\query/edges]]></fr:code> and <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/paths]]></fr:code> represent the two modes.</fr:li></fr:ol></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>656</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00WY</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00WY.xml</fr:route><fr:title>The syntax of a relational query</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WW</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A relational query takes the following form:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\query/rel{mode}{polarity}{relation}{addr}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>In the above, <fr:code>mode</fr:code> and <fr:code>polarity</fr:code> must evaluate to mode and polarity constants as in <fr:ref
addr="jms-00WZ"
href="jms-00WZ.xml" />; <fr:code>relation</fr:code> must evaluate to a relation symbol as in <fr:ref
addr="jms-00WX"
href="jms-00WX.xml" />.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>658</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00X0</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00X0.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Expressing built-in queries</fr:title><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WW</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The built-in basic queries can be expressed in terms of <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00WY.xml"
addr="jms-00WY"
title="The syntax of a relational query"><fr:code><![CDATA[\query/rel]]></fr:code></fr:link> in the following way:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\def\my-query/author[x]{
 \open\query
 \rel{\edges}{\incoming}{\rel/authors}{\x}
}

\def\my-query/taxon[x]{
 \open\query
 \rel{\edges}{\incoming}{\rel/taxa}{\x}
}

\def\my-query/tag[x]{
 \open\query
 \rel{\edges}{\incoming}{\rel/tags}{\x}
}]]></fr:pre></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>660</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00X2</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00X2.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Querying the (back)links and context a given tree</fr:title><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WW</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Both the backlinks and (forward) links of a given tree can be computed using a query to the <fr:code><![CDATA[\rel/links]]></fr:code> relation, and the context (immediate parents) of a given tree can be obatined from the <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/transclusion]]></fr:code> relation:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\def\query/backlinks[x]{
 \open\query
 \rel{\edges}{\incoming}{\rel/links}{\x}
}

\def\query/links[x]{
 \open\query
 \rel{\edges}{\outgoing}{\rel/links}{\x}
}

\def\query/context[x]{
 \open\query
 \rel{\edges}{\incoming}{\rel/transclusion}{\x}
}]]></fr:pre></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>662</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00X4</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00X4.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Querying a coslice of the transclusion preorder</fr:title><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WW</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We can also write a query to compute the set of trees <fr:em>underneath</fr:em> a given tree in the transclusion preorder (including the original tree) — in other words, the coslice.</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\def\query/transclusion-coslice[x]{
 \open\query
 \rel{\paths}{\outgoing}{\rel/transclusion}{\x}
}]]></fr:pre></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>664</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00X1</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00X1.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Unions and intersections of families of relational queries</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WS</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A further primitive query-former is the union or intersection of a certain <fr:em>family</fr:em> of relational queries indexed in the <fr:em>results</fr:em> of a fixed query. These are written as follows:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\query/union-fam{q}{mode}{polarity}{relation}
\query/isect-fam{q}{mode}{polarity}{relation}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>The meaning of the above is to first compute the set of trees <fr:code>x,...</fr:code> satisfying the query <fr:code>q</fr:code>, and then take the (union, intersection) of all the induced relational queries <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/rel{mode}{polarity}{relation}{x}]]></fr:code>. With this feature in hand, it becomes possible to compute the full bibliography of a given tree, or find the full list of contributors to a given tree (as opposed to only its immediate contributors).</fr:p><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>666</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00X3</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00X3.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Querying the bibliography of a given tree</fr:title><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00X1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We can define a macro to compute the bibliography of a given tree, making use of <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/transclusion-coslice]]></fr:code> from <fr:ref
addr="jms-00X4"
href="jms-00X4.xml"
taxon="Example" />.</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\def\query/bibliography[x]{
 \open\query
 \isect{
  \union-fam{\transclusion-coslice{\x}}{\edges}{\outgoing}{\rel/links}
 }{
  \taxon{reference}
 }
}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>The above code first accumulates all the outgoing links from the given tree and any of its children, and then restricts (by intersection) to those with taxon <fr:code>reference</fr:code>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>668</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00X5</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00X5.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Querying all hereditary contributors to a tree</fr:title><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00X1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We can use the union of families of relational queries to compute the set of (proper) <fr:link
type="local"
href="tfmt-000T.xml"
addr="tfmt-000T"
title="Contributor to a tree"><fr:em>contributors</fr:em></fr:link> to a given tree. This is slightly subtle, because if a bibliographic tree is transcluded, we do not want its contributors to be included.</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\def\query/contributors[x]{
 \open\query
 \union-fam{
  \isect{
   \tree-under{\x}
  }{
   \compl{
    \taxon{reference}
   }
  }
 }{\edges}{\outgoing}{\rel/contributors}
}]]></fr:pre></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:p>In the future, the support for query-indexed families of queries might be generalised to allow arbitrary queries in the components rather than only relational ones. The current version of the feature should be viewed as somewhat provisional.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="false"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>670</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00WT</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00WT.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Warning</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WS</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>It is strongly recommended that inexperienced users of <fr:link
type="local"
